basicPropertyValues.val: An ontology that collects all species specific life stage ontologies.

definition.val: A spatiotemporal region encompassing some part of the life cycle of an organism.
Temporal interval that defines lizard life from the prenatal stage until late adult stage.
Lizard life cycle that starts with fertilization and ends with hatching.

comments: Following internal fertilization, early embryogenesis clearly proceeds within the oviduct in lizards genus Anolis, and most eggs are laid at the Early limb-bud stage of development (Stage 4). Juvenile lizards genus Anolis hatch with a snout-to-vent length of about 1.6 cm, after 22-27 days of incubation(see http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=17724661).

definition.val: Lizard developmental stage that covers the period from hatching until 8 months old, when individuals reach sexual maturity.

comments: Both male and female juvenile green anoles reach sexual maturity by eight months of age (see http://animaldiversity.ummz.umich.edu/accounts/Anolis_carolinensis/).

definition.val: Lizard developmental stage that refers to a sexually mature adult lizard, which is usually over 8 months old.
Lizard developmental stage that refers to a lizard who is over 8 and under 24 months old.

comments: Green anoles have a lifespan ranging from 2 to 8 years, determined largely by predation. Lifespan in captivity is similar to that in the wild, approximately 4 to 6 years (see http://animaldiversity.ummz.umich.edu/accounts/Anolis_carolinensis/). We arbitraly consider 2 years as the upper limit for the adult stage, before aged stage. This is to improve as far as information is available.

definition.val: Lizard developmental stage that refers to a lizard who is over 24 months old.

comments: Green anoles can live up to seven years in captivity (see http://genomics.senescence.info/species/entry.php?species=Anolis_carolinensis). We arbitraly consider over 2 years as the starting point for aged stage. This is to improve as far as information is available.

definition.val: A spatiotemporal region encompassing some part of the life cycle of an organism.

Cow life cycle that starts with fertilization and ends at birth.

comments: Bovine gestation is 277 days (about 9 months) (see http://genomics.senescence.info/species/entry.php?species=Bos_taurus). Depending on the breed, the gestation time slightly varies (see http://embryology.med.unsw.edu.au/embryology/index.php?title=Bovine_Development). Gestational length is commonly calculated based on recorded insemination (see PMID:30452469), so actually this is the fetal age.

comments: Female cows reach sexual maturity by 548 days of age(see http://genomics.senescence.info/species/entry.php?species=Bos_taurus).

definition.val: Cow developmental stage that refers to a sexually mature adult cow, which is usually over 1.5 years old.
Mature stage that refers to a cow who is over 1.5 and under 12 years old, the usual upper limit for breeding age.

comments: Females appear to remain fertile for about 12 years (see http://genomics.senescence.info/species/entry.php?species=Bos_taurus).

definition.val: Mature stage that refers to a cow who is over 12 years old, the usual upper limit for breeding age.

comments: Cows have been known to live over 20 years.

definition.val: Embryo development period during the first 3 months of gestation, up to day 90 of development.

comments: Toward the end of the third month (60 to 90 days), the four stomachs may be recognized. The fetus measures 14 cm. in length. The scrotum is present (see https://embryology.med.unsw.edu.au/embryology/index.php?title=Bovine_Development#General_Overview).

definition.val: Embryo development period during the second trimester of gestation, from over day 90 up to day 180 of development.

comments: At end of the sixth month, the eyelashes are more developed. The foetus is about 46 cm. long. The whole body is still naked excepting the lips and eyelids (see https://embryology.med.unsw.edu.au/embryology/index.php?title=Bovine_Development#General_Overview).

definition.val: Embryo development period during the last trimester of gestation, from the seventh month (over 180 days) of development until birth.

comments: A few long hairs appear at the end of the tail, and in the beginning of the ninth month, the whole body is covered with hair and increases greatly in size. The fetus measures from 80 to 100 cm. In the beginning of the tenth month, the fetus becomes mature. (see https://embryology.med.unsw.edu.au/embryology/index.php?title=Bovine_Development#General_Overview).

definition.val: Embryo development period during the first month of gestation.

comments: The embryo is 9 to 10 mm long and the first signs of extremities appear (see https://embryology.med.unsw.edu.au/embryology/index.php?title=Bovine_Development#General_Overview).

definition.val: Embryo development period during the second month of gestation (30 to 60 days).

comments: The extremities develop. The pharyngeal cleft closes in the beginning of this month. First indication of the hoof. (see https://embryology.med.unsw.edu.au/embryology/index.php?title=Bovine_Development#General_Overview).

definition.val: Embryo development period during the third month of gestation (60 to 90 days).

comments: The extremities develop. The pharyngeal cleft closes in the beginning of this month. First indication of the hoof. (see https://embryology.med.unsw.edu.au/embryology/index.php?title=Bovine_Development#General_Overview).

definition.val: Embryo development period during the fourth month of gestation (90 to 120 days).

comments: In the beginning of the fourth month the hoofs become quite distinct; they are firm, non-transparent, and have a yellow color. The fetus is about 24 cm. long (see https://embryology.med.unsw.edu.au/embryology/index.php?title=Bovine_Development#General_Overview).

definition.val: Embryo development period during the fifth month of gestation (120 to 150 days).

comments: In the beginning of the fifth month the first tentaculse (tactile hairs) appear on the lips, chin, upper eyelid, and orbital arch. The teats are plainly visible. The testicles descend into the scrotum. The fetus is about 35 cm. long (see https://embryology.med.unsw.edu.au/embryology/index.php?title=Bovine_Development#General_Overview).

definition.val: Embryo development period during the sixth month of gestation (150 to 180 days).

comments: The eyelashes are more developed. The foetus is about 46 cm. long. The whole body is still naked excepting the lips and eyelids (see https://embryology.med.unsw.edu.au/embryology/index.php?title=Bovine_Development#General_Overview).

definition.val: Embryo development period during the seventh month of gestation (180 to 210 days).

comments: At the end of this month a few long hairs appear at the end of the tail; also hairs about the coronet and on the spots where the horns appear. The foetus is about 60 cm. long (see https://embryology.med.unsw.edu.au/embryology/index.php?title=Bovine_Development#General_Overview).

comments: Embryo develops in 155 days (see http://genomics.senescence.info/species/entry.php?species=Capra_hircus). Bgee_curator_notes: Bgee prenatal stage definition differs from Uberon embryonic stage definition by the notion of birth for stage ending, while Uberon ends with fully formed embryo. We maybe have to correct our too precise definition.

definition.val: A stage at which the organism is a single cell produced by means of sexual reproduction.
Prenatal stage consisting of division of cells in the early goat embryo.

comments: Unsegmented egg was observed approximately 30h after insemination, see https://embryology.med.unsw.edu.au/embryology/index.php?title=Paper_-_The_early_development_of_the_goat_(1942). We decide to start cleavage stage at day 1 post fertilization.

The first cleavage division did not occur until 24-36 h after ovulation, but the following two divisions occurred at about 12-h intervals, see PMID: 2621707. Completion of first cleavage was observed 48h after mating, see https://embryology.med.unsw.edu.au/embryology/index.php?title=Paper_-_The_early_development_of_the_goat_(1942).

Egg at 4-cell stage was recovered from the fallopian tubes of a female killed 60h after mating, see https://embryology.med.unsw.edu.au/embryology/index.php?title=Paper_-_The_early_development_of_the_goat_(1942).

60h after ovulation 23/26 (88%) embryos collected had 8-cells, see PMID: 2621707. Eggs recovered between 60h and 85h have completed the third cleavage while still in the fallopian tube, see https://embryology.med.unsw.edu.au/embryology/index.php?title=Paper_-_The_early_development_of_the_goat_(1942).

The first 16-cell embryo was collected 84 h after ovulation; the 8- to 16-cell stage was prolonged compared to the previous two cell cycles and lasted about 24-36 h; embryos also began to compact at the 8 16-cell stage, see PMID: 2621707.

definition.val: Cleavage stage during which the goat embryo develops from 16 cells up to 128 cells.

comments: Embryos also began to compact at the 8 16-cell stage and the following 3 cell cycles occurred more rapidly lasting between 10 and 12 h, see PMID: 2621707. Fertile goat eggs enter the uterus sometime between the close of the fourth day and the beginning of the fifth day after mating, see https://embryology.med.unsw.edu.au/embryology/index.php?title=Paper_-_The_early_development_of_the_goat_(1942).

definition.val: Embryonic stage that is an early stage of embryonic development in animals and is produced by cleavage of a fertilized ovum, with formation of a central fluid-filled cavity called the blastocoel.

comments: On the 6th day after fertilization the goat embryo shows structural changes indicative of transformation into a blastocyst. At this time the central embryonic cells exhibit signs of strong growth, and the blastocyst cavity begins to form, see https://zootechnical.com/article/148044/en.

definition.val: Embryonic stage defined by complex and coordinated series of cellular movements that occurs at the end of cleavage.

comments: Further embryonic development involves the disappearance of the zona pellucida, rapid growth and development of the blastulas, and the formation of the germ layer, i.e. gastrulation. In this form the embryo is implanted in the wall of the uterus, where subsequent stages of embryonic development take place. The endoderm, ectoderm and mesoderm formed during gastrulation form most of the organs and tissues, see https://zootechnical.com/article/148044/en.

definition.val: Embryonic gastrula stage during which the primitive streak bulges into the pro-amniotic cavity and forms the amniotic fold; the exocoelom appears; the allantoic bud first appears, gastrulation continues and the node becomes visible.

comments: Embryonic age 7 dpc (day post coitum), (range 6.5-7.5 dpc). Refers to human CarnegieStage08.

definition.val: Embryonic stage defined by formation of a tube from the flat layer of ectodermal cells known as the neural plate.

comments: This term was obsoleted as it was the only child associated to MmusDv:0000017., This stage starts the emergence of the central nervous system at embryonic age 7.5 dpc (day post coitum).

definition.val: Embryonic stage called presomite stage and defined by the formation of the neural plate.

comments: This stage starts the emergence of the central nervous system at embryonic age 7.5 dpc (day post coitum).

definition.val: Embryonic stage at which the ectoderm, endoderm, and mesoderm develop into the internal organs of the organism.
Organogenesis stage during which first somites become visible.

comments: Embryonic age 8 dpc (day post coitum). Refers to human CarnegieStage09.

definition.val: Organogenesis stage defined by the turning of the embryo; initiated in embryos with 6-8 pairs of somites and usually completed in embryos with 14-16 pairs of somites.

comments: Embryonic age 8.5 dpc (day post coitum). Refers to human CarnegieStage10.

definition.val: Organogenesis stage during which the rostral extremity of the neural tube closes in embryos with usually about 15-18 somite pairs. Late in the stage the 3rd branchial arch becomes visible.

comments: Embryonic age 9 dpc (day post coitum). Refers to human CarnegieStage11.

definition.val: Organogenesis stage during which the posterior neuropore forms and the condensation of the forelimb bud becomes apparent near the 8th-12th somite pairs.

comments: Embryonic age 9.5 dpc (day post coitum). Refers to human CarnegieStage12.

definition.val: Organogenesis stage during which the posterior neuropore closes and the hind limb bud becomes visible at the level of the 23rd-28th somites.

comments: Embryonic age 10 dpc (day post coitum). Refers to human CarnegieStages 13 to 15.

definition.val: Organogenesis stage defined by the deepening of the lens pit and the first appearance of the physiological umbilical hernia.

comments: Embryonic age 10.5 dpc (day post coitum). Refers to human CarnegieStages 13 to 15.

definition.val: Organogenesis stage during which the lens vesicle gradually closes and the nasal pits start to form. The rapid growth of the brain is striking.

comments: Embryonic age 11 dpc (day post coitum). Refers to human CarnegieStages 13 to 15.

definition.val: Organogenesis stage during which the lens vesicle becomes completely closed and detached from the ectoderm, and peripheral margins of the eye become well defined.

comments: Embryonic age 11.5 dpc (day post coitum). Refers to human CarnegieStage16.

definition.val: Organogenesis stage during which the handplate develops angles corresponding to the future digits, and tongue and brain vesicles are clearly visible.

comments: Embryonic age 12 dpc (day post coitum). Refers to human CarnegieStage17.

definition.val: Organogenesis stage during which the digit widths and locations can be discerned, and the pinna rapidly develops and forms a crest at right angles to the head.

comments: Embryonic age 13 dpc (day post coitum). Refers to human CarnegieStages 18 and 19.

definition.val: Organogenesis stage during which the fingers are clearly visible and the long bones of the limbs are present.

comments: Embryonic age 14 dpc (day post coitum). Refers to human CarnegieStages 20 to 23.

definition.val: life cycle that follows the embryonic development stage and during which further organogenesis and histogenesis occur.

comments: This term was obsoleted to follow human developmental ontology structure.

definition.val: Prenatal stage that starts with the fully formed embryo and ends at birth.

comments: This stage describes the four Theiler stages that are commonly reported as equivalent to the human fetal period in the literature. They are anyway defined by embryonic days.

definition.val: Fetal stage during which the toes separate and hair follicles are present in the cephalic region but not at the periphery of the vibrissae.

comments: Embryonic age 15 dpc (day post coitum). Refers to the human fetal period.

definition.val: Fetal stage during which the umbilical hernia disappears and there is a corresponding increase in the size of the peritoneal sac.

comments: Embryonic age 16 dpc (day post coitum). Refers to the human fetal period.

definition.val: Fetal stage during which the thickened skin forms wrinkles and the subcutaneous veins are less visible.

comments: Embryonic age 17 dpc (day post coitum). Refers to the human fetal period. Refers to rat Standard Witschi Stage 34 (see http://php.med.unsw.edu.au/embryology/index.php?title=Mouse_Stages#Theiler_Stage_25).

definition.val: Fetal stage defined by long whiskers and during which the eyes are barely visible through the closed eyelids.

comments: TS26 is used for the period from embryonic day 18 up to birth itself. [https://github.com/tfhayamizu]. Refers to rat Standard Witschi Stage 35 (see http://php.med.unsw.edu.au/embryology/index.php?title=Mouse_Stages#Theiler_Stage_26).

definition.val: Stage that refers to the newborn mouse, aged E19-20, P0. Description of anatomical structures related to this stage corresponds to the first days of the mouse life. Used for postnatal days 0 through 3.

comments: TS27 is used for annotation of postnatal days 0 through 3 (P0 to P3). This is a somewhat arbitrary cut-off but seems to best fit the data we have encountered. TS28 is then used from postnatal day 4 onward. [https://github.com/tfhayamizu]

definition.val: Development stage that defines the postnatal period, all the way through adulthood.

comments: TS27 is used for annotation of postnatal days 0 through 3 (P0 to P3). This is a somewhat arbitrary cut-off but seems to best fit the data we have encountered. TS28 is then used from postnatal day 4 onward. [https://github.com/tfhayamizu]

definition.val: Immature stage that refers to a mouse which is over 1 week and under 6 weeks old.

comments: This term was made obsolete due to discussion at https://github.com/obophenotype/developmental-stage-ontologies/issues/23. [ANiknejad]

definition.val: Immature stage that refers to a mouse which is over 4 weeks and under 7 weeks old.

comments: This term was obsoleted as it is not fully accepted as a defined developmental stage in the literature. This stage describes the age at which mice are usually used as adolescent mouse models in the literature.

definition.val: Mouse developmental stage that refers to a mouse which is over 5 weeks old.

comments: This term was obsoleted to include the mature stage into the ontology. Both terms have the same children, but contains of children (children of children) differ. The organisation of the postnatal development time in mouse is debatable, literature usually refers to mature or immature mice, with milestone around 6-8 weeks post-natal.

definition.val: Mouse life cycle that starts with fertilization and ends with birth.

comments: It is commonly accepted that mouse reaches sexual maturity by six weeks of age (see http://www.ahc.umn.edu/rar/breeding.html).

definition.val: Early immature stage that refers to the newborn mouse which is over 1 and under 8 days old.

Theiler developmental stage 10 during which the tissue at the posterior end of the primitive streak bulges into the pro-amniotic cavity and forms the amniotic fold.

comments: Refers to MS (mid-streak) stage in Downs and Davies staging of gastrulating mouse embryos (PMID: 8269852, 1993).

definition.val: Theiler developmental stage 10 during which small cavities coalesce to form a single cavity in the mesoderm of the posterior amniotic fold, the exocoelom.

comments: Refers to MS-LS (mid-streak to late streak) stage in Downs and Davies staging of gastrulating mouse embryos, 1993 (see http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/8269852).

definition.val: Theiler developmental stage 10 during which the allantoic bud first appears, gastrulation continues and the node becomes visible.

comments: Refers to MS-LS (mid-streak to late streak) stage in Downs and Davies staging of gastrulating mouse embryos, 1993 (see http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/8269852).

definition.val: Theiler developmental stage 12 defined by unturned embryo with first appearance of somite pairs 1-4 and during which the allantois extends further into the exocoelom. Maxillary components of the 1st branchial arch become prominent. The preotic sulcus is visible in the 2-3 somite embryo. The cardiogenic plate begins to form and the foregut pocket is clearly visible.

comments: Embryonic age 8 dpc (day post coitum). Refers to human CarnegieStage09.

definition.val: Theiler developmental stage 12 defined by unturned embryo with first appearance of somite pairs 5-7 and during which neural closure occurs in the region of the 4th and 5th somites, extending in both directions from this site. Headfolds are particularly prominent. Optic placodes are first evident and become indented to form the optic pits. The heart rudiment develops rapidly. The allantois contacts the chorion at the end of this stage.

comments: Embryonic age 8 dpc (day post coitum). Refers to human CarnegieStage09.

definition.val: Mouse developmental stage that refers to a sexually mature adult mouse which is over 6 weeks old.

Embryonic neurula stage during which the neural plate formation occurs and the amniotic cavity is sealed off into three distinct cavities - the amniotic cavity, the exocoelom and the ectoplacental cleft.
Mouse developmental stage that covers the period from P4 starting at TS28 until 5 weeks old.

comments: It is commonly accepted that mouse reaches sexual maturity by six weeks of age (see http://www.ahc.umn.edu/rar/breeding.html). We start this stage at P4 because TS27 'newborn' stage is not defined as a postnatal stage.

Temporal interval that defines platypus life from the prenatal stage until late adult stage.
Platypus life cycle that starts with fertilization and ends with hatching.

comments: Estimated gestation periods are 27 days and incubation periods are 10 days (see http://animaldiversity.ummz.umich.edu/accounts/Ornithorhynchus_anatinus/#reproduction).

definition.val: Platypus developmental stage that covers the period from hatching until 1.5 year old, when individuals usually reach sexual maturity.

comments: Male and female platypus reach sexual maturity by 548 days of age (see http://genomics.senescence.info/species/entry.php?species=Ornithorhynchus_anatinus).

definition.val: Platypus developmental stage that refers to a sexually mature adult platypus, which is over about 1.5 year old.

comments: Male and female platypus reach sexual maturity by 548 days of age (see http://genomics.senescence.info/species/entry.php?species=Ornithorhynchus_anatinus).

definition.val: Mature stage that refers to a adult platypus which is over 1.5 and under 10 years old, the usual upper limit for breeding age.

comments: Females are thought likely to become sexually mature in their second year, with breeding confirmed still to take place in animals over 9 years old. (see http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Platypus). We decided to consider 10 years the upper limit for breeding age, before aged stage.

definition.val: Mature stage that refers to a adult platypus which is over 10 years.

comments: There is little information on the longevity of platypuses. They can live up to 12 years in the wild (see http://www.mspca.org/programs/wildlife-resources/species-information/about-platypuss.html) and one captive specimen was at least 22.6 years old when it died (see http://genomics.senescence.info/species/entry.php?species=Ornithorhynchus_anatinus). Over 10 years old is usually no more a breeding age.

definition.val: Platypus developmental stage that covers the period from birth until late adulthood.
A spatiotemporal region encompassing some part of the life cycle of an organism.
Temporal interval that defines sheep life from the prenatal stage until late adult stage.
Sheep life cycle that starts with fertilization and ends at birth.

comments: Embryo develops in 146 days (see http://genomics.senescence.info/species/entry.php?species=Ovis_aries). Bgee_curator_notes: Bgee prenatal stage definition differs from Uberon embryonic stage definition by the notion of birth for stage ending, while Uberon ends with fully formed embryo. We maybe have to correct our too precise definition.

definition.val: Sheep developmental stage that covers the period from birth until about 18 months old, when individuals reach sexual maturity.

comments: sheep reach sexual maturity by 914 days of age for male, 548 days for female (see http://genomics.senescence.info/species/entry.php?species=Ovis_aries).

definition.val: Sheep developmental stage that covers the period from birth until about 6 months old, at which point individuals wean.

comments: Age of weaning is 182 days (see http://genomics.senescence.info/species/entry.php?species=Ovis_aries).

definition.val: Sheep developmental stage that covers the period from 6 months old, when individuals wean, until about 18 months old, when individuals reach sexual maturity.

comments: sheep reach sexual maturity by 914 days of age for male, 548 days for female (see http://genomics.senescence.info/species/entry.php?species=Ovis_aries).

definition.val: Sheep developmental stage that refers to a sexually mature adult sheep, which is usually over 18 months old.
Mature stage that refers to a sheep who is over 18 months old and under about 6 years old.

comments: Domestic sheep exhibit gradual senescence. The onset of reproductive senescence has been shown to occur at 5 and 6 years of age. One captive specimen lived 22.8 years (see http://genomics.senescence.info/species/entry.php?species=Ovis_aries).

definition.val: Mature stage that refers to a sheep who is over 6 years old.

comments: Domestic sheep exhibit gradual senescence. The onset of reproductive senescence has been shown to occur at 5 and 6 years of age. One captive specimen lived 22.8 years (see http://genomics.senescence.info/species/entry.php?species=Ovis_aries).

definition.val: A stage at which the organism is a single cell produced by means of sexual reproduction.
Prenatal stage consisting of division of cells in the early sheep embryo.

comments: First division occurs 24 hours after fertilisation, see http://dx.doi.org/10.1016/j.smallrumres.2016.12.016, Table 1.

definition.val: Cleavage stage during which the sheep embryo undergoes the first 3 days of development.

comments: At this stage, the 2-8 cells egg is still in the oviduct, and the morula (1632 cells) stage embryo enters the uterus from the oviduct on day 4 after mating (day 0 = estrus/mating) (see doi:10.1530/rep.1.00398).

definition.val: Cleavage stage during which the sheep embryo (16-32 cells egg) undergoes the fourth and fith days of development.

comments: The morula (1632 cells) stage embryo enters the uterus from the oviduct on day 4 after mating (day 0 = estrus/mating) (see doi:10.1530/rep.1.00398).

definition.val: Embryonic stage during which the sheep embryo develops into a spherical blastocyst and performs zona hatching.

comments: The blastocyst is formed on day 6, and the zona pellucida is shed between days 8 and 9. The blastocyst is spherical on day 8, measures 200 micron in diameter and contains approximately 300 cells (see doi:10.1530/rep.1.00398).

definition.val: Embryonic stage during which the sheep embryo measures 400900 micron in diameter and contains approximately 3000 cells.
Embryonic stage during which the sheep embryo starts to elongate into tubular blastocyst.
Embryonic stage during which the sheep embryo has elongated markedly, reaching a length of 1022 mm.

comments: Formation of the primitive streak (start of the gastrula stage) occurs at day 12 (see http://dx.doi.org/10.1016/j.smallrumres.2016.12.016, Table 1).

definition.val: Embryonic stage during which the conceptus, first located in the uterine horn ipsilateral to the corpus luteum, elongates into the contralateral horn.
Embryonic stage during which the filamentous conceptus is about 10 cm long and the primitive streak appears, with somites soon thereafter.
Embryonic stage during which the apposition stage starts, with first intimate cellular contacts between the trophoblast and the uterine epithelium.
Embryonic stage during which the trophoblast begins to adhere firmly to the endometrial lumenal epithelium.
Embryonic stage during which the tubular blastocyst reaches a length of 25 cm or more by day 17 and resembles a long filament composed mainly of extraembryonic trophoblast.
Embryonic stage during which the embryo undergoes the twentieth day of development, while adhesion is fully completed.
Sheep developmental stage that covers the period from birth until late adulthood.
Embryonic stage that is an early stage of embryonic development in animals and is produced by cleavage of a fertilized ovum, with formation of a central fluid-filled cavity called the blastocoel.

comments: TE Spencer (see doi:10.1530/rep.1.00398) reports formation of the sheep blastocyst at day 6.

definition.val: Embryonic stage defined by complex and coordinated series of cellular movements that occurs at the end of cleavage.
Embryonic stage defined by formation of a tube from the flat layer of ectodermal cells known as the neural plate.

comments: Formation of the neural groove in sheep appears at day 15 (see http://dx.doi.org/10.1016/j.smallrumres.2016.12.016, Table 1).

definition.val: Embryonic stage at which the ectoderm, endoderm, and mesoderm develop into the internal organs of the organism.
A spatiotemporal region encompassing some part of the life cycle of an organism.
Temporal interval that defines rabbit life from fertilisation to death.
rabbit life cycle stage that starts with fertilisation and ends with birth.

comments: estimated gestation period is 30 days (http://genomics.senescence.info/species/entry.php?species=Oryctolagus_cuninculus).

definition.val: rabbit life cycle stage that starts at birth and ends at the reach of sexual maturity (2.6 months post-birth).

comments: rabbits reach sexual maturity at 730 days old: http://genomics.senescence.info/species/entry.php?species=Oryctolagus_cuninculus).

definition.val: rabbit life cycle stage that starts at sexual maturity (2.6 months post-birth) and ends with death.

Approximately 4- 5 weeks after hatching the young fish makes its way through the gravel and begins active feeding. At this point they are approximately 3 inches long and are called "fry" or fingerlings. One year after hatching the fry change coloring and acquire distinctive markings on their flanks which now distinguishes them as "parr" (http://www.uky.edu/~agrdanny/flyfish/life.htm).

comments: Pig reach sexual maturity by 768 days of age for male, 334 days for female. While achieving sexual maturity much earlier, males do not typically mate until they are about 5 years old (see http://genomics.senescence.info/species/entry.php?species=Sus_scrofa).

definition.val: Pig developmental stage that covers the period from birth until about 2 months old, at which point individuals wean.

comments: Age of weaning is 56 days (see http://genomics.senescence.info/species/entry.php?species=Sus_scrofa). Piglets are highly precocious and neonates appear with open eyes, good muscle tone and well developed skin and hair (see http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=23874755). Within minutes of being born, or sometimes seconds, they will attempt to suckle. The piglets are born with sharp teeth and fight to develop a teat order as the anterior teats produce a greater quantity of milk (see http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Piglet_%28animal%29).
